SIMPLE: mantle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: mantle
<hw>man"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>mantel</ets>, OF. <ets>mantel</ets>, F. <ets>manteau</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>mantellum</ets>, <ets>mantelum</ets>, a cloth, napkin, cloak,
mantle (cf. <ets>mantele</ets>, <ets>mantile</ets>, towel, napkin);
prob. from <ets>manus</ets> hand + the root of <ets>tela</ets> cloth.
See <er>Manual</er>, <er>Textile</er>, and cf. <er>Mandil</er>,
<er>Mantel</er>, <er>Mantilla</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A loose garment to be worn over other garments; an
enveloping robe; a cloak.</def> <specif>Hence,</specif> figuratively,
<def>a covering or concealing envelope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The] children are clothed with <qex>mantles</qex> of satin.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The green <qex>mantle</qex> of the standing pool.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now Nature hangs her <qex>mantle</qex> green⟦br⟧
On every blooming tree.</q> <rj><qau>Burns.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Same as
<er>Mantling</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The external fold,
or folds, of the soft, exterior membrane of the body of a mollusk. It
usually forms a cavity inclosing the gills. See <xex>Illusts.</xex> of
<er>Buccinum</er>, and <er>Byssus</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any
free, outer membrane.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The back of a bird
together with the folded wings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A mantel. See
<er>Mantel</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The outer wall and casing of a blast furnace, above
the hearth.</def> <rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Hydraulic Engin.)</fld> <def>A penstock for a water
wheel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>The highly viscous shell of hot
semisolid rock, about 1800 miles thick, lying under the crust of the
Earth and above the core. Also, by analogy, a similar shell on any other
planet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mantle
<hw>Man"tle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mantled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mantling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To cover or
envelop, as with a mantle; to cloak; to hide; to disguise.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mantle
<hw>Man"tle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To unfold and spread
out the wings, like a mantle; -- said of hawks. Also used
figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ne is there hawk which <qex>mantleth</qex> on her perch.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or tend his sparhawk <qex>mantling</qex> in her mew.</q>
<rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My frail fancy fed with full delight.⟦br⟧
Doth bathe in bliss, and <qex>mantleth</qex> most at ease.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To spread out; -- said of wings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The swan, with arched neck⟦br⟧
Between her white wings <qex>mantling</qex> proudly, rows.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To spread over the surface as a covering; to
overspread; <as>as, the scum <ex>mantled</ex> on the
pool</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though <qex>mantled</qex> in her cheek the blood.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To gather, assume, or take on, a covering, as froth,
scum, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a sort of men whose visages⟦br⟧
Do cream and <qex>mantle</qex> like a standing pond.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor bowl of wassail <qex>mantle</qex> warm.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mantled</ent>⟦br⟧
